quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  70,1,"<span class="h">An asker asked{1}</span><span class=""h"">about</span>a punishment sure to come",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “A flood has flooded with a punishment sure to come…” According to the dialect of the tribes of <i>Hijaz</i>, the narration of Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far means exactly the same as all the others.</span>
  70,2,"for the deniers, that none can repel—"
  70,3,"from Allah, Lord of the Ways of Ascent."
  70,4,"Unto Him the angels and the Spirit ascend on a day the duration of which is fifty thousand years."
  70,5,"So be<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>patient with beautiful patience."
  70,6,"Indeed, they see it distant,"
  70,7,"but We see it near—"
  70,8,"on the day when the sky is like molten brass,"
  70,9,"and the mountains are like tufted wool,"
  70,10,"and no intimate<i class=""s"">(friend) </i><span class=""h"">asks{1} </span>his intimate<i class=""s"">(friend) </i>—",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far and Al-Bazzi in one of his narrations read it as: “…and no intimate (friend) is asked (about) his intimate (friend)…”</span>
